FIREBLIGHT, POME FRUIT - USA: (NEW YORK), STREPTOMYCIN RESISTANT STRAINS
************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 9 Jan 2012
Source: Physorg [edited]
http://www.physorg.com/news/2012-01-strep-resistant-blight-york-orchards.html


Cornell plant pathologists have issued a warning to New York apple and pear growers. For 50 years, fireblight has been kept at bay using the antibiotic streptomycin, but streptomycin-resistant strains of the disease were recently found in 4 locations in Wayne and Ontario counties.

"This is a serious situation. The rapid identification of this outbreak positions us to implement a coordinated plan leading up to next year's [2012] growing season," said Herb Aldwinckle, New York State Agricultural Experiment Station (NYSAES), who is developing guidelines to reduce the threat.

Strep-resistant fire blight was 1st identified in California in 1971, and since then, it has been found in Washington, Oregon, Missouri, and southwest Michigan. Diseased nursery trees from Michigan were the source of an outbreak in New York in 2002, but eradication appears to have been effective. For this current infection, sampling was necessarily limited in late fall [2011], so the full extent of the outbreak is as yet unclear.

Aldwinckle said the fact that one of the sites is a nursery does complicate the management plan. Some infections might not be immediately visible, so there's a possibility that trees with the strain were inadvertently shipped to growers. He advises to examine trees carefully after planting.

He is also exploring other ways to eradicate the blight. "The antibiotic kasugamycin is as effective and is not used in human or veterinary medicine," he said. Cornell is leading an application for an emergency registration from the Environmental Protection Agency to use kasugamycin next spring [2012].

[Byline: Stacey Shackford]

